<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-697-786  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 697 786.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  June 1990 n596A p16(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Arrays ease mixed-signal ASIC design; CMOS arrays providehigh-performance analog capability. (application-specificintegrated circuit)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Winner, Greg; Kaylor, Scott; Shen, Vince.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Mixed-signal (analog and digital) integrated circuits (MSICs) arebeing implemented as standard cells, bipolar arrays and CMOSarrays.andP;  CMOS may be the preferred technology for MSICs,particularly when low power dissipation is an importantconstraint.andP;  Advantages of CMOS arrays for MSICs include rapidlydeveloping analog technology, mature design-automation tools withlowest recurring engineering costs, accurate filtering capability,and easy implementation of high-resolution A/D and D/A converters.andO;Debits include limited available CMOS arrays and less efficientuse of silicon.andP;  Examples of CMOS MSICs are Silicon Systems Inc's(Tustin, CA) 6700 family, which is based on a tile architecture.andO;The five members of the family, their high-performance analogcapabilities and their design using Mentor Graphics workstationsand the IDM design-automation system are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Silicon Systems Inc. (product development).andO;Topic:     Integrated CircuitsApplication-Specific Integrated CircuitsGate ArraysAnalog Integrated CircuitsCircuit DesignProduct DevelopmentComplementary Metal Oxide Semiconductors.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   The Silicon Systems 6700 CMOS array. (chart)Dedicated servo signal-processor circuit. (chart)Distributor-less automobile ignition system using a mixed-signalIC. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>